Survival Analysis in R

Survival analysis is a statistical method used to analyze the time until an event of interest occurs. It is widely used in medical research, engineering, social sciences, and other fields where time-to-event data is collected. In this tutorial, we will cover the basics of survival analysis and demonstrate how to perform it in R.

1. What is Survival Analysis?

Survival analysis is used to analyze the time until an event occurs. The event could be: - Death (in medical studies) - Failure of a machine (in engineering) - Relapse of a disease - Customer churn (in business)

The goal is to estimate the probability of survival (or event occurrence) over time and identify factors that influence survival.

2. Key Concepts in Survival Analysis

a. Survival Function \(S(t)\)

The survival function \(S(t)\) gives the probability that an individual survives beyond time \(t\): \[ S(t) = P(T > t) \]

\(T\) (Time Until Event): This is the time until the event occurs.
\(t\) (Specific Time Point): This is the particular time value you’re interested in. You want to know the probability of surviving beyond this time.

Example:

Imagine a study on the survival of patients after a cancer diagnosis. If S(5 years) = 0.6, this means there’s a 60% chance that a patient will survive for more than 5 years after their diagnosis.

  • Event: Death of the patient

  • \(T\) The time until the patient dies (a random variable)

  • \(t\) A specific time point, like 5 years

When you say “S(5 years) = 0.6”, you’re saying:

  • The probability (P) that the time until the patient dies (T) is greater than 5 years (t) is equal to 0.6 (or 60%).

In simpler terms: There’s a 60% chance that the patient will survive for more than 5 years after their diagnosis.

What does the \(T\) mean? The time until the patient dies (a random variable)

The survival function, S(t), uses this random variable T to calculate probabilities.

Example

Let’s say we have three patients:

  • Patient A lives for 2 years after diagnosis.

  • Patient B lives for 5 years after diagnosis.

  • Patient C lives for 10 years after diagnosis.

For these patients:

  • T (for Patient A) = 2 years

  • T (for Patient B) = 5 years

  • T (for Patient C) = 10 years

b. Hazard Function \(h(t)\)

The hazard function \(h(t)\) gives the instantaneous risk of the event occurring at time \(t\), given that the individual has survived up to time \(t\): \[ h(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \to 0} \frac{P(t \leq T < t + \Delta t \mid T \geq t)}{\Delta t} \]

Let’s unpack it step by step:

  1. \(Δt (Delta t)\): This represents a very small increment of time. Think of it as a tiny step forward in time from t.

  2. \(T\): As before, T is the random variable representing the actual time until the event occurs.

  3. \(t\): This is the specific time point we’re interested in. We want to know the risk of the event happening right now, at time t.

  4. \(t ≤ T < t + Δt\): This part means that the event occurs between time t and time t + Δt. So, the event hasn’t happened yet at time t, but it does happen within that tiny window of time Δt.

  5. \(T ≥ t\): This is a conditional statement. It means “given that the individual has survived up to time t”. We’re only considering individuals who have made it to time t.

  6. \(P(t ≤ T < t + Δt | T ≥ t)\): This is the conditional probability of the event occurring between t and t + Δt, given that the individual has survived until t. It’s the probability of the event happening in that small window, knowing the individual is still “at risk” at time t.

  7. \([ … ] / Δt\): We divide the conditional probability by the small time increment Δt. This gives us a rate. It’s like how we calculate speed by dividing distance by time.

  8. \(lim (Δt → 0)\): This is the crucial part. It says we take the limit as Δt approaches zero. We make that tiny time window Δt infinitesimally small. This is what makes the hazard function instantaneous. It’s the risk at the exact moment t, not over a small interval.

In simpler terms:

The hazard function \(h(t)\) asks: “If an individual has survived to time t, what is the instantaneous probability that the event will happen right now?”

Scenario: We’re studying the risk of a heart attack in patients who have been diagnosed with a specific heart condition.

1. Time (t): Let’s say we’re interested in the risk at t = 5 years after diagnosis.

2. Time Increment (Δt): We consider a tiny window of time just after 5 years, say 5 years and 1 day (or even a smaller increment). Δt would be 1 day (or whatever small unit we choose). In the hazard function’s equation, we eventually make Δt infinitely small.

3. Random Variable (T): T represents the actual time until a patient experiences a heart attack. This is a random variable because we can’t predict exactly when any individual patient will have a heart attack (if they ever do).

4. Event: The event of interest is a heart attack.

5. Conditional Probability: P(5 ≤ T < 5 + Δt | T ≥ 5)

This is the probability that a patient will have a heart attack between 5 years and 5 years + Δt (our tiny window), given that they have survived without a heart attack up to 5 years.

  • T ≥ 5: This condition is essential. It means we are only considering patients who have not had a heart attack in the first 5 years after diagnosis.

  • 5 ≤ T < 5 + Δt: This means the patient has a heart attack within that small window after 5 years.

6. The Hazard Rate: h(5)

The hazard rate at 5 years, h(5), is calculated by taking the conditional probability (step 5), dividing it by Δt, and then letting Δt approach zero.

  • Dividing by Δt: This turns the probability into a rate. It’s like saying, “What’s the probability of a heart attack per unit of time (e.g., per day, per month)?”

  • Letting Δt approach zero: This makes the rate instantaneous. It’s not the rate over a small window; it’s the risk at the exact moment of 5 years.

In simpler terms: h(5) represents the instantaneous risk of a heart attack at the precise moment of 5 years after diagnosis, given that the patient has not had a heart attack before that time.

c. Censoring

Censoring occurs when the event of interest has not been observed for some individuals during the study period. There are three types of censoring:

- Right-censoring: The event has not occurred by the end of the study.

- Left-censoring: The event occurred before the study started.

- Interval-censoring: The event occurred within a known time interval (occurs when you don’t know the exact time an event of interest happened, but you know it occurred within a specific time interval.).

3. Data Preparation

Survival data typically includes:

- Time: The time until the event or censoring.

- Event: A binary indicator (1 = event occurred, 0 = censored).

- Covariates: Predictor variables (e.g., age, treatment group).

Example Dataset

We will use the lung dataset from the survival package in R. This dataset contains survival data for patients with advanced lung cancer.

4. Kaplan-Meier Survival Curve

The Kaplan-Meier estimator is a non-parametric method used to estimate the survival function.

Steps:

  1. Create a survival object using the Surv() function.
  2. Fit the Kaplan-Meier model using the survfit() function.
  3. Plot the survival curve.
# Create a survival object
surv_obj <- Surv(lung$time, lung$status)

# Fit the Kaplan-Meier model
km_fit <- survfit(surv_obj ~ 1, data = lung) # The 1 on the right-hand side means that there are no predictor variables (covariates) being considered.
print(km_fit)
## Call: survfit(formula = surv_obj ~ 1, data = lung)
## 
##        n events median 0.95LCL 0.95UCL
## [1,] 228    165    310     285     363

  • Call: survfit(formula = surv_obj ~ 1, data = lung): This shows the function call. surv_obj is the survival object, ~ 1 in the formula indicates that we’re modeling survival for the entire dataset as a single group (no stratification).

  • n: This is the total number of individuals in the dataset (228).

  • events: This is the total number of events (e.g., deaths) observed in the dataset (165).

  • median: This is the estimated median survival time. It’s the time at which 50% of the individuals are expected to have experienced the event. In this case, the median survival time is 310 (presumably days, but the time units depend on how the Surv object was created).

  • 0.95LCL: This is the lower limit of the 95% confidence interval for the median survival time (285).

  • 0.95UCL: This is the upper limit of the 95% confidence interval for the median survival time (363).

# Convert survfit object to a data frame for ggplot2
km_data <- data.frame(time = km_fit$time, surv = km_fit$surv)

# Function to create the base ggplot2 plot (no lines initially)
create_km_plot <- function() {
  km_data <- data.frame(time = km_fit$time, surv = km_fit$surv)
  ggplot(km_data, aes(x = time, y = surv)) +
    geom_step() +
    labs(x = "Time (Days)", y = "Survival Probability", title = "Kaplan-Meier Survival Curve") +
    scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
    theme_bw()
}

# Function to add lines (modified for ggplot2)
add_line <- function(gg_plot, x = NULL, y = NULL) {
    km_data_local <- data.frame(time = km_fit$time, surv = km_fit$surv) # needed to access km_fit inside the function
    if (!is.null(x)) {
        idx <- which.min(abs(km_data_local$time - x))
        y_val <- km_data_local$surv[idx]

        gg_plot <- gg_plot +
            geom_segment(x = x, y = 0, xend = x, yend = y_val, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
            geom_segment(x = 0, y = y_val, xend = x, yend = y_val, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
            geom_point(x = x, y = y_val, color = "red", size=3) #Make the point bigger
        cat("Survival probability at time", x, "is approximately", y_val, "\n")

    } else if (!is.null(y)) {
        idx <- which.min(abs(km_data_local$surv - y))
        x_val <- km_data_local$time[idx]

        gg_plot <- gg_plot +
            geom_segment(x = x_val, y = 0, xend = x_val, yend = y, color = "blue", linetype = "dashed") +
            geom_segment(x = 0, y = y, xend = x_val, yend = y, color = "blue", linetype = "dashed") +
            geom_point(x = x_val, y = y, color = "blue", size=3) #Make the point bigger
        cat("Time at survival probability", y, "is approximately", x_val, "\n")

    } else {
        print("Please provide either x or y value.")
    }
    return(gg_plot) # Return the modified ggplot object
}

# Example usage (demonstrates restarting the plot):

gg_km <- create_km_plot() # Create the initial plot
print(gg_km)

gg_km <- add_line(gg_km, x = 150) # Add a line
## Survival probability at time 150 is approximately 0.7931001
print(gg_km)

gg_km <- create_km_plot() # Restart the plot (clears previous lines)
gg_km <- add_line(gg_km, y = 0.5) # Add a different line
## Time at survival probability 0.5 is approximately 310
print(gg_km)

gg_km <- create_km_plot() # Restart the plot again
gg_km <- add_line(gg_km, x = 200) # Add another line
## Survival probability at time 200 is approximately 0.6802729
print(gg_km)

5. Log-Rank Test

The log-rank test is used to compare the survival curves of two or more groups.

Example: Compare Survival by Gender

# Fit the Kaplan-Meier model by gender
km_fit_gender <- survfit(surv_obj ~ sex, data = lung)

# Plot the survival curves
plot(km_fit_gender, col = c("blue", "red"), xlab = "Time (Days)", ylab = "Survival Probability", main = "Survival by Gender")
legend("topright", legend = c("Male", "Female"), col = c("blue", "red"), lty = 1)

# Perform the log-rank test
logrank_test <- survdiff(surv_obj ~ sex, data = lung)
print(logrank_test)
## Call:
## survdiff(formula = surv_obj ~ sex, data = lung)
## 
##         N Observed Expected (O-E)^2/E (O-E)^2/V
## sex=1 138      112     91.6      4.55      10.3
## sex=2  90       53     73.4      5.68      10.3
## 
##  Chisq= 10.3  on 1 degrees of freedom, p= 0.001

  • Call: survdiff(formula = surv_obj ~ sex, data = lung):
    This shows the function call that generated the output. surv_obj represents the survival object (created using Surv()), sex is the grouping variable, and lung is the dataset.

  • N:
    This is the total number of individuals in each group. sex=1 has 138 individuals, and sex=2 has 90 individuals.

  • Observed:
    This is the number of events (e.g., deaths) observed in each group. sex=1 had 112 events, and sex=2 had 53 events.

  • Expected:
    This is the number of events that would be expected in each group if there were no difference in survival between the groups. These expected values are calculated under the null hypothesis of no difference.

  • (O-E)^2/E:
    This is the contribution of each group to the overall chi-squared statistic. It’s calculated as the squared difference between the observed and expected number of events, divided by the expected number of events. A larger value indicates a greater difference between observed and expected, suggesting a difference in survival.

  • (O-E)^2/V:
    This is a slightly different version of the contribution to the chi-squared statistic, where V is the variance of the difference between observed and expected events. This version is often used in more complex survival analysis scenarios. In this simple two-group comparison, it leads to the same result as the other calculation of the chi-squared component.

  • Chisq= 10.3:
    This is the overall chi-squared statistic, calculated by summing the (O-E)^2/E (or (O-E)^2/V) values for each group. It measures the overall difference between the observed and expected number of events across all groups.

  • on 1 degrees of freedom:
    This indicates the degrees of freedom for the chi-squared test. In a two-group comparison, the degrees of freedom is always 1.

  • p= 0.001:
    This is the p-value associated with the chi-squared statistic. It represents the probability of observing a chi-squared statistic as large as the one calculated (or larger), assuming there is no real difference in survival between the groups (the null hypothesis is true). A small p-value (typically less than 0.05) indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis. 1

We will use a more professional package.

We’ll use the function ggsurvplot() [in Survminer R package] to produce the survival curves for the two groups of subjects.

           palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"))

  • ggsurvplot(km_fit_gender, …):
    This initiates the ggsurvplot function, which is specifically designed for visualizing survival analysis results. km_fit_gender is the output of a Kaplan-Meier survival analysis, likely created using the survfit() function. It contains the survival data and group information (in this case, gender).

  • pval = TRUE:
    This displays the p-value from a log-rank test (or other appropriate test) comparing the survival curves of the different gender groups. A low p-value (typically < 0.05) suggests a statistically significant difference in survival between the genders.

  • conf.int = TRUE:
    This adds confidence intervals around the survival curves. These intervals provide a range of plausible values for the true survival probabilities at each time point. Wider intervals indicate more uncertainty.

    • Where do plausible values ​​come from? Here’s a breakdown:

      • Original Data: The original data consists of the event times (or censoring times) for each individual in your study. This is the foundation upon which everything else is built.

      • Kaplan-Meier Estimation: The Kaplan-Meier method uses the original event times to estimate the survival probabilities at various time points. This gives you a survival curve.

      • Standard Errors: The Kaplan-Meier method also calculates standard errors for the survival probability estimates. These standard errors quantify the uncertainty in the estimated probabilities. They are calculated based on the number of events and the number at risk at each time point.

      • Confidence Intervals: Confidence intervals are calculated using the survival probability estimates and their standard errors. A common method is to use a normal approximation (or other suitable distribution) to create the interval. The formula for a confidence interval is generally something like:

      • Estimated Probability ± (Critical Value * Standard Error)

      • Plausible Values: The plausible values are the range of values within the calculated confidence interval. They are derived from the original data because the original data is used to calculate the Kaplan-Meier estimates and their standard errors, which are then used to create the confidence interval.

  • risk.table = TRUE:
    This adds a risk table below the survival plot. The risk table shows the number of individuals still at risk (i.e., have not experienced the event of interest) at various time points. This is crucial for understanding how the number of subjects in each group changes over time, as censoring (loss to follow-up or end of study) occurs.

  • risk.table.col = “strata”:
    This colors the risk table entries according to the strata (gender in this case). This makes it easy to visually distinguish the number at risk in each group.

  • linetype = “strata”:
    This makes the survival curves themselves have different line types (e.g., solid, dashed) for each gender. This further enhances visual distinction between the groups.

  • surv.median.line = “hv”:
    This draws a horizontal and vertical line on the plot indicating the median survival time for each group. The median survival time is the time at which 50% of the individuals in a group are expected to have experienced the event.

  • ggtheme = theme_bw():
    This applies the black and white theme from the ggplot2 package to the plot. This provides a clean and professional look.

  • palette = c(“#E7B800”, “#2E9FDF”):
    This sets the colors for the survival curves (and risk table, if risk.table.col is used). It uses a gold/yellow (#E7B800) and a blue (#2E9FDF) color for the two gender groups.

The Kaplan-Meier plot can be interpreted as follow:

  • The horizontal axis (x-axis) represents time in days, and the vertical axis (y-axis) shows the probability of surviving or the proportion of people surviving.

  • The lines represent survival curves of the two groups.

  • A vertical drop in the curves indicates an event. The vertical tick mark on the curves means that a patient was censored at this time.

  • At time zero, the survival probability is 1.0 (or 100% of the participants are alive).

  • At time 250, the probability of survival is approximately 0.55 (or 55%) for sex=1 and 0.75 (or 75%) for sex=2.

  • The median survival is approximately 270 days for sex=1 and 426 days for sex=2, suggesting a good survival for sex=2 compared to sex=1

summary(km_fit_gender)$table
##       records n.max n.start events    rmean se(rmean) median 0.95LCL 0.95UCL
## sex=1     138   138     138    112 326.0841  22.91156    270     212     310
## sex=2      90    90      90     53 460.6473  34.68985    426     348     550

Let’s interpret the table:

  • sex:
    The grouping variable. In this case, it’s comparing two groups (sex=1 and sex=2). These could represent any two groups you’re comparing (e.g., treatment vs. control, male vs. female, etc.).

  • n.max:
    The total number of individuals in each group at the start of the study. It’s important to remember that in survival analysis, the number of individuals at risk can change over time due to events (like death or the event of interest occurring) or censoring (loss to follow-up).

  • n.start:
    Same as n.max in this context. It’s redundant and only included for consistency.

  • events:
    The number of events observed in each group. In survival analysis, an “event” is the outcome you’re studying (e.g., death, disease recurrence, etc.).

  • rmean:
    This is the expected number of events in each group under the null hypothesis (i.e., assuming there’s no difference in survival between the groups). It’s not the observed rate. This is a crucial point.

  • se(rmean):
    The standard error of the expected number of events. This reflects the uncertainty in the expected number of events.

  • median:
    The median survival time for each group. This is the time at which 50% of the individuals in the group are expected to have experienced the event.

  • 0.95LCL:
    The lower confidence limit for the median survival time.

  • 0.95UCL:
    The upper confidence limit for the median survival time.

The cumulative hazard function

The cummulative hazard is commonly used to estimate the hazard probability. It’s defined as H(t)=−log(survivalfunction)=−log(S(t)). The cumulative hazard (H(t)) can be interpreted as the cumulative force of mortality. In other words, it corresponds to the number of events that would be expected for each individual by time t if the event were a repeatable process.

ggsurvplot(km_fit_gender,conf.int = TRUE,
           risk.table.col = "strata", # Change risk table color by groups
           ggtheme = theme_bw(), # Change ggplot2 theme
           palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"),
           fun = "cumhaz")

6. Cox Proportional Hazards Model

The Cox proportional hazards model is a semi-parametric model used to assess the effect of covariates on survival.

Steps:

  1. Fit the Cox model using the coxph() function.
  2. Interpret the results.
lung$sex <- ifelse(lung$sex == 1 , "male", "female")

# Fit the Cox model
cox_fit <- coxph(surv_obj ~ age + sex, data = lung)

# Summarize the model
summary(cox_fit)
## Call:
## coxph(formula = surv_obj ~ age + sex, data = lung)
## 
##   n= 228, number of events= 165 
## 
##             coef exp(coef) se(coef)     z Pr(>|z|)   
## age     0.017045  1.017191 0.009223 1.848  0.06459 . 
## sexmale 0.513219  1.670660 0.167458 3.065  0.00218 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
##         exp(coef) exp(-coef) lower .95 upper .95
## age         1.017     0.9831     0.999     1.036
## sexmale     1.671     0.5986     1.203     2.320
## 
## Concordance= 0.603  (se = 0.025 )
## Likelihood ratio test= 14.12  on 2 df,   p=9e-04
## Wald test            = 13.47  on 2 df,   p=0.001
## Score (logrank) test = 13.72  on 2 df,   p=0.001

Simple Interpretation:

  • Hazard Ratio (HR): The effect of a covariate on the hazard of the event.
    • HR > 1: Increased risk of the event.
    • HR < 1: Decreased risk of the event.
  • p-value: Significance of the covariate.

1. Call:

  • coxph(formula = surv_obj ~ age + sex, data = lung): This line tells you what function was used (coxph for Cox proportional hazards) and how the model was specified.

    • surv_obj: This is your survival object, created using the Surv() function. It contains the time-to-event information (e.g., survival time and censoring status).

    • ~ age + sex: This specifies that the model includes age and sex as predictor variables (covariates) for survival.

    • data = lung: This indicates that the data for the analysis is in the lung dataset (a standard dataset in R’s survival package).

2. Sample Size and Events:

  • n = 228, number of events = 165:

    • n = 228: There were 228 individuals in the study.

    • number of events = 165: Out of the 228 individuals, 165 experienced the event of interest (e.g., death, disease progression) during the study period. The remaining individuals were censored (e.g., lost to follow-up, study ended before they experienced the event).

3. Coefficients:

This section is the heart of the model output.

  • coef: These are the estimated coefficients from the Cox model. They represent the effect of the covariates on the log-hazard. It’s important to understand these are on the log scale.

  • exp(coef) (Hazard Ratio): This is the exponentiated coefficient. It’s the hazard ratio (HR), and it’s much easier to interpret than the raw coefficient.

    • age (1.017191): The hazard ratio for age is 1.017. This means that for every one-unit increase in age (e.g., one year older), the hazard of the event increases by about 1.7%. (1.017 - 1 = 0.017, or 1.7%).

    • sexmale (1.670660): The hazard ratio for sexmale is 1.671. Because sex is a categorical variable, R has created a dummy variable. sexmale represents the effect of being male compared to the reference category, which is female. This HR means that males have a hazard that is 1.67 times (or 67% higher) the hazard for females.

  • se(coef): The standard error of the coefficient. It measures the precision of the coefficient estimate.

  • z: The z-statistic. It’s calculated by dividing the coefficient by its standard error. It’s used to test the statistical significance of the covariate.

  • Pr(>|z|) (p-value): The p-value associated with the z-statistic. It tells you the probability of observing a coefficient as extreme as the one you got, assuming there’s no real effect of the covariate.

    • age (0.06459): The p-value for age is 0.065. This is not statistically significant at the conventional 0.05 level. This means that, in this model, there’s not enough evidence to conclude that age has a significant effect on survival.

    • sexmale (0.00218): The p-value for sexmale is 0.002. This is statistically significant at the 0.05 level (and even at the 0.01 level). This means there’s strong evidence that sex has a significant effect on survival.

4. Confidence Intervals:

  • exp(coef) exp(-coef): The hazard ratio and its inverse.

  • lower .95 upper .95: The 95% confidence interval (CI) for the hazard ratio. It gives you a range of values within which you are 95% confident the true hazard ratio lies.

    • age (0.999, 1.036): The 95% CI for the age hazard ratio includes 1. This is consistent with the non-significant p-value for age. If the CI includes 1, it means that a hazard ratio of 1 (no effect) is plausible.

    • sexmale (1.203, 2.320): The 95% CI for the sexmale hazard ratio does not include 1. This is consistent with the significant p-value for sexmale.

5. Concordance:

  • Concordance = 0.603 (se = 0.025): The concordance statistic (C-statistic) measures how well the model predicts the order of events. A C-statistic of 0.5 indicates no predictive ability (like random chance), and a C-statistic of 1 indicates perfect predictive ability. 0.603 suggests that the model has moderately good predictive ability.

6. Overall Model Tests:

These tests assess the overall significance of the model (whether at least one of the covariates is significant).

  • Likelihood ratio test, Wald test, Score (logrank) test: These are three different statistical tests that all test the same null hypothesis (that all coefficients are zero). In large samples, they usually give similar results.

  • on 2 df: Degrees of freedom. This is equal to the number of predictor variables in the model (2: age and sex).

  • p = 9e-04, p = 0.001, p = 0.001: These are the p-values for the overall tests. They are all very small (much less than 0.05), indicating that the overall model is statistically significant. This means that at least one of the covariates (in this case, sex) is significantly related to survival.

ggforest(cox_fit, data = lung)

7. Conclusion

In this tutorial, we covered the basics of survival analysis and demonstrated how to perform it in R. Specifically, we: 1. Prepared survival data. 2. Estimated the survival function using the Kaplan-Meier estimator. 3. Compared survival curves using the log-rank test. 4. Assessed the effect of covariates using the Cox proportional hazards model.

Survival analysis is a powerful tool for analyzing time-to-event data. With R, you can easily perform these analyses and gain insights into the factors that influence survival.
